<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sporadic Violence Erupts in N.Irish Catholic Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Sporadic violence broke out
Saturday during protests against a traditional Protestant
Apprentice Boys' parade in Northern Ireland's second largest city
of Londonderry.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 nationalist demonstrators were involved in the
disturbances in the city center, with 130 petrol bombs thrown at
the police.
</P>
<P>
Protesters also fired catapults and set off fireworks. Six
vehicles were hijacked, of which two were burnt.
</P>
<P>
Seven protesters were arrested while at least eight police
officers were injured, but none was seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
But the huge security operation, launched amid police warnings
that republicans were planning to use the event to stir up
violence, kept nationalists and marchers apart. The parade itself,
involving up to 10,000 people and 150 bands, passed off
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The parade was held amid a huge security presence and
opposition from residents of the mainly Catholic and nationalist
Bogside area of the city.
</P>
<P>
It followed violence in the Lower Ormeau Road area of the
Northern Ireland capital of Belfast Saturday morning, when
nationalists attempted to block the route of another Apprentice
Boys parade.
</P>
<P>
Scuffles broke out as police wearing riot gear moved 200
demonstrators who were sitting in the road. Nineteen police
officers and a number of protesters were injured during the
clashes in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Parades by the Protestant Orange Order and the Apprentice Boys
have been the subject of controversy for many years in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The marchers view the parades as a traditional expression of
their culture, but in Catholic nationalist areas they are often
viewed as triumphalist and intimidating.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's parade is to commemorate the 1689 Siege of
Londonderry, known as Derry to its largely Catholic population,
when Protestant apprentices shut the gates of the walled city
against the forces of the Catholic King James II in December 1688.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Protestants died before the city in that war and
Londonderry is now 75 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
The Londonderry and Belfast parades were earlier given the
go-ahead by the Northern Ireland Parades Commission.
</P>
<P>
The two marches took place on the eve of the first anniversary
of a car bomb in the town of Omagh that killed 29 people and
wounded hundreds more on August 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The anniversary was marked Saturday by shops closing on the
little high street where shoppers were killed. A prayer service
was held on the spot where the bombs went off. The town's main
remembrance ceremony will be held Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Talks on implementing a Northern Irish peace deal signed in
April last year have been frozen until September as Protestant
politicians refuse to share power with Catholic republicans in the
Sinn Fein party until its guerrilla ally, the Irish Republican
Army, disarms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
