<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Pension Firms Urged To Keep It Simple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Pension firms in Britain are
being urged to simplify their products after a survey estimated
more than 5 million adults had not begun saving for their
retirement.
</P>
<P>
The research by consumer analyst group Mintel discovered 5.4
million adults thought a pension scheme would be too expensive for
them for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
It also found 40 percent of families did not know when they
would start a pension because they believed they could not afford
one.
</P>
<P>
It has already announced that the British government is set to
launch stakeholder pension schemes in 2001 to give more people
access to a pension.
</P>
<P>
Despite the government's efforts to encourage greater
retirement provision many family adults still do not own a
pension.
</P>
<P>
Mintel questioned 1,800 adults as a representative sample. And
25 percent said they expected to have to work after retiring from
full-time jobs to supplement their retirement income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
