<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hostages in Liberia Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 100 hostages, including six
 European aid workers, who had been held by Liberian rebels in the
past few days were released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They are now in a camp of the Doctors Without Borders, a France
 based charity group, two of whose aid workers were also among the
 captives seized Wednesday morning when armed men entered their
compound in Kolahun, Lofa County near the Sierra Leone and Guinea
border.
</P>
<P>
"They are apparently unharmed. They will be arriving in
Conakry this afternoon," said a British diplomat in Senegal.
Britain has no embassy in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Among the six European captives, four are British, and the
other two were Norwegian and Italian, who are working with charity
organizations of Merlin and Doctors Without Borders. They were in
the country helping to rebuild hospitals when they were seized,
according to reports.
</P>
<P>
The hostages had crossed over to Guinea by foot, for the
Liberian side of the Liberia-Guinea border has been closed
according to President Charles Taylor's order.
</P>
<P>
The group, mostly Liberian civilians, had been allowed to leave
the rebel's camp by foot Friday. Guinea had agreed to the passing
of its territory by the released hostages on "humanitarian
considerations".
</P>
<P>
The group seemed to have been caught in the middle of fighting
in northern Liberia on Wednesday when Liberian government forces
were battling heavily with rebels believed to be based in Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor Wednesday declared a state of
 emergency in Lofa County, where he said insurgents had captured
several towns overnight.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said government troops were rushing to the front and
called on all "able-bodied men" to report for military service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
