<HEADLINE> Banking Sector in Oman on Way to Y2K Compliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The banking sector of Oman is
drawing up comprehensive contingency plans to achieve compliance
to the year 2000 computer problem, also known as the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in a Y2K follow-up meeting held at the
Central Bank of Oman (CBO) on Saturday, according to an Oman News
Agency report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Due to some programming defects rooted in their early
development stage, computers can only identify the year in the
last two digits, which means they might mistake the year 2000 for
1900. It is feared that chaos may occur when the year 2000 comes
due to this defect as computers are now so widely used.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector is "well on its way toward achieving Y2K
compliance, having already addressed the remedial and replacement
requirements," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was chaired by Iqbal Ali Khamis, CBO vice president
and chairman of the National Y2K Task Force, and was attended by
senior CBO officials, members from commercial banks and
representatives from Omani Telecommunications Corporation (OTC).
</P>
<P>
Given the heavy reliance of banks on the telecommunications
sector, an OTC representative at the meeting assured that most of
their systems were in final stages of testing. British Telecom,
which was helping in this phase, would certify their compliance.
</P>
<P>
"OTC is forming a high level committee to take responsibility
of the contingency plan that is being designed by British
Telecom," the representative said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
