<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Confirms Approval of Libyan Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government
reiterated its approval of the five-point peace plan submitted by
Libya on reconciliation between the Sudanese government and the
opposition force.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese News Agency on Saturday quoted Foreign Minister
Mustafa Osman Ismail as saying that as the Sudanese government has
accepted the Libyan initiative, the ball is now in the hands of the
opposition for achieving national unity in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The report said a Libyan official will arrive in Khartoum on
Monday to discuss the details of the peace plan with Sudanese
officials.
</P>
<P>
The proposed peace plan involves immediate ceasefire, direct
dialog between the government and the opposition and immediate
suspension of hostile propagandas against each other.
</P>
<P>
It calls for forging a committee to determine the time and
venue of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The plan also outlines Libya's responsibility to coordinate
with other neighboring countries in working for a solution to the
Sudanese issue.
</P>
<P>
Civil war is raging in Sudan since 1983 between the government
troops and the forces of the Sudanese People's Liberation Army
(SPLA) led by John Garang, which is fighting for independence from
the Muslim-dominated central government and for the establishment
of a separate state in southern Sudan where most of the population
believe in Christianism or animism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
