<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Party Leader Arrested at S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police Saturday
confirmed the arrest of Zambia's Barotse Patriotic Front leader
Imasiku Mutangelwa who was holed up in the South African High
Commission in Lusaka after seeking asylum there, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Mutangelwa's party was suspected of backing an armed rebellion
by Namibian separatists in the Caprivi Strip last week in which 14
people were killed.
</P>
<P>
He took refuge in the South African High Commission last
Thursday after claiming that his life was in danger.
</P>
<P>
Zambian police Inspector-General Francis Ndhlovu told SAPA that
 Mutangelwa was arrested at the High Commission Friday around 9
p.m. (1900 GMT) after a bench warrant was issued by the Zambian
High Court for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
Ndhlovu said Mutangelwa had failed to appear before a court at
Mongu in west Zambia Thursday on charges of allegedly "causing
death by dangerous driving".
</P>
<P>
Ndhlovu said Mutangelwa would not remain in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the South African and Zambian governments in an
effort to clarify Mutangelwa's status were not resolved before his
arrest, SAPA quoted a Foreign Ministry spokesman as saying
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mutangelwa asked for political asylum after he was summoned to
police headquarters in Lusaka following a statement in which he
allegedly expressed support for separatists in Namibia's Caprivi
Strip.
</P>
<P>
This followed alleged reports quoting him as saying that Lozis
from Zambia's Western Province had started crossing into the
Caprivi Strip to support secessionist rebels.
</P>
<P>
The people from western Zambia, formerly known as Barotseland,
are from the same Lozi ethnic group as the Caprivians in Namibia.
</P>
</TEXT>
