<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Egyptian Journalists Sentenced to Jail for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Three Egyptian journalists were
sentenced to two-year imprisonment with labor Saturday for
libeling the country's deputy prime minister, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The editor-in-chief of the Al-Shaab newspaper, the fiery
mouthpiece of the opposition Labor Party, Magdi Hussein, reporter
Salah Bedewei and cartoonist Essam-Eddin Hanafi were also fined by
the South Cairo Criminal Court 20,000 Egyptian pounds (5,900 U.S.
dollars) each, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
A fourth journalist of the newspaper, Adel Hussein, a columnist
and the editor's brother, was fined 20,000 pounds for defamation
to a lesser degree. Adel Hussein is also deputy chairman of the
Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
The court convicted them of libeling Egyptian Deputy Prime
Minister Youssef Wali in a series of articles and cartoons,
published over nearly a year, that accused him of "treason" and
"working as an agent for a foreign state."
</P>
<P>
Judge Hassib al Betrawi said it has been proven that "these
accusations are groundless."
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaab called Wali, who is also the minister of agriculture,
a traitor and accused him of destroying Egypt's economy for having
signed several agricultural agreements with Israel for the supply
of seed, fertilizers and technology to arrest desertification.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time that Magdi Hussein has been convicted
under a 1996 press law. Last year he and another Al-Shaab
journalist were sentenced to two years in prison with labor for
libeling a former interior minister. The Supreme Court freed them
after they reached a settlement with the minister.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaab is published by the Labor Party, which is allied to
the Muslim Brotherhood, Egypt's strongest Islamic movement, and
which opposes peace with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-14 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Supreme Leader Appoints New Judiciary Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei issued a decree here Saturday to appoint a prominent
religious scholar, Ayatollah Mahmoud Hashemi, as new head of the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Hashemi replaces Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi, a conservative,
whose two, five-year terms end this year. The new judiciary chief
is to be officially introduced on August 17.
</P>
<P>
According to Iran's Constitution adopted on July 28, 1989,
judiciary head exercises the supervisor-general executing judicial
power, and appoints chief justice of the Supreme Court and
prosecutor-general.
</P>
<P>
In his decree, Khamenei said the judiciary is a powerful arm
of the Islamic system and fulfilling its great mission will
guarantee security and real sustainable tranquility in the
society.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing judiciary head has been attacked for his
conservative approaches such as imprisoning reform-minded
officials and shutting down moderate newspapers. During the
student demonstrations and street riots on August 8-13 sparked by
the closing of the moderate "Salam" newspaper, the protesters
urged him to resign.
</P>
<P>
"Highlighting the difficult path that the judiciary has taken
so far, especially in recent years, the leader pointed out the
great success it has achieved despite the occasionally widespread
and deep opposition," the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Local media differ in describing the new judiciary chief. Some
brand Hashemi, 51, extremely conservative, others call him a
central but conservative-lean cleric. He has been keeping a low
profile so far and his political orientation is not clear. He was
born in 1948 and began religious studies after completing
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
He has held various positions in the powerful Experts
Assembly, the Expediency Council and the Supreme Management
Council of the Qom Theological Seminary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
