<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Accommodations for Namibian Secessionists, SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Saturday reiterated that "there is no
accommodation for secessionist movements" in any country in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The SADC secretariat said this in a statement correcting media
reports attributed to SADC executive secretary Kaire Mbuende on
the situation in Namibia's Caprivi.
</P>
<P>
A report Friday attributed to Mbuende said that the SADC
"Council (of Ministers) would consider Namibia's complaints that
Botswana was harboring key rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
The SADC secretariat dismissed the report as baseless and "a
sign of irresponsible reporting."
</P>
<P>
The SADC secretariat pointed out that Mbuende never granted an
interview, adding that he neither mentioned Botswana nor touched
on the Botswana-Namibia relations during a media briefing on the
upcoming SADC summit Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat presented a transcript of a tape recording of
Mbuende's comments on the Caprivi situation.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is very clear that the territorial integrity of
Namibia and any of our SADC member states is inviolable and we are
going to defend the territorial integrity," Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no accommodation for secessionist movements," he
noted, adding that the situation in Caprivi "is not as critical
as it was initially reported or thought and it has been
substantially brought under control".
</P>
<P>
The SADC secretariat noted that the friendly and cordial
relations between Namibia and Botswana were recently attested to
during the 9th session of the Namibia/Botswana Joint Commission
on Defense and Security in Namibian capital Windhoek earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, believed to belong to secessionist Caprivi
Liberation Army, launched an attack on the Katima Mulilo police
station, the nearby airport and occupied the offices of the
state-owned Namibian Broadcasting Corporation radio station in a
strip of land in northeastern Namibia on August 2.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were later suppressed by government forces, in which
15 people were believed to have been killed in skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leader Mishake Muyongo, who is now in exile in Denmark,
was quoted by a South African television as saying that Caprivi
has never been part of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Muyongo, who was former leader of Namibia's major opposition
Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, fled to neighboring Botswana last
October, days before the Namibian government claimed to have
uncovered a secessionist plot in the Caprivi.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 armed men followed him .
</P>
<P>
Muyongo was allegedly granted asylum by the Botswanan
authorities in February this year and was later resettled in
Denmark." 
</P>
</TEXT>
