<HEADLINE> Sub-regional Summit on Liberia-Guinea Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Liberia, Guinea, Sierra Leone and
Cote D'ivoire are to hold a summit on the alleged rebel's
incursion into Liberia

from Guinea, according to reports reaching here from Abidjan,
commercial capital of Cote D'ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Cote D'ivoire's Foreign Minister Amara Essy said in Abidjan
Saturday that the meeting will take place in the Guinean capital
of Conakry next week.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is to get Presidents Lansana Conte of Guinea and
Charles Taylor around the table," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tension between both countries rose after an abduction of the
western aid workers by rebel gunmen in an area where Liberian
government troops are fighting armed rebels. Liberia has been
accusing Guinea, its northern neighbor, of harboring "dissident
forces" whom it blamed for the abduction.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Liberia has lodged a protest with the United
Nations Security Council against its fellow member of the Economic
Community of West African States, which has placed its troops
or the West Africa Peace Keeping Force in Liberia in alert.
</P>
<P>
Late Friday, the rebels freed the six western hostages along
with other 90 Liberian civilians, making a similar hostage-taking
drama like the one in S. Leone last week. 
</P>
