<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Conflicts Pose Challenge to SADC (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The summit, held under the theme "SADC in the next millennium:
working together for peace, progress and prosperity", will run
from August 17 to 18, with the first day devoted to grand
celebrations for the 19th anniversary of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The summit was preceded by several preparatory meetings by
SADC officials and by a council of ministers gathering on Friday
and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued at the just-concluded ministerial meeting
said that among issues to be discussed are the 24-year-old Angola
civil war, the conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC), tensions between Angola and Zambia and preparations for
general elections in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
"On Angola, there is a need for concerted effort at regional
and international levels to resolve the stalemate in the
implementation of the Lusaka Protocol," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos in 1994 signed a peace
pact with Jonas Savimbi, leader of the rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), under which Savimbi was
to be given the vice-presidency of the country in return for
halting the civil war.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA has since reneged on the peace deal and restarted
the war after capturing key diamond-producing regions. Close to
1.7 million people have been either displaced or become refugees
during the fighting.
</P>
<P>
SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende said at the meeting
that intervention by SADC troops in the Angolan civil war cannot
be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
"SADC intervention cannot be ruled out" in Angola, he said
without elaborating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
