<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Conflicts Pose Challenge to SADC (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 by Yu Dabo
</P>
<P>
The heads of state will also discuss the year-old civil war in
the DRC, where Tutsi-led rebels are trying to topple president
Laurent Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
Three SADC countries -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- last
year intervened militarily in the DRC's civil war, saying they
were supporting a fellow member state against rebel aggression.
</P>
<P>
On July 10, Kabila and his allies -- Angola, Namibia and
Zimbabwe-- signed a cease-fire agreement in Zambian capital
Lusaka, as did the backers of the rebels, Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
However, the main rebel movement, the Congolese Rally for
Democracy, had declined to sign amid a leadership row that has
split the movement in two.
</P>
<P>
The SADC statement said it was "pleasing to note" that Angola
and Zambia "are amicably resolving their differences."
</P>
<P>
Relations between the neighbors soured in June amid
allegations of Lusaka's support of UNITA rebels fighting the
Luanda regime.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, Namibia's President Sam Nujoma is likely to
raise the recent attack by secessionist rebels on his country's
northeastern Caprivi Region, an official said.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 people were killed in clashes between security
forces and the rebels on August 2.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of the Caprivi and that of arms trafficking in the
region are very important to the summit," said the official, who
refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende said SADC's position on the Caprivi Strip was clear --
"that there is no accommodation for separatist movements in any
country of the region".
</P>
<P>
The wars in Angola and the DRC as wells as the situation in
the Caprivi Strip will dominate the summit, he said.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here said the political and military
conflicts in the region will test the collective will of SADC
member states. There will be no way to achieve South African
President Thabo Mbeki's African renaissance vision before
solutions are found to end the conflicts, they noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
