<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Pseudo-science Book Series Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A series of books on fighting
pseudo-science, titled "The Teahouse of Mr. Science", made its
debut today in Changsha, capital of Hunan Province in central
China.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony to mark the publication, Yu Guangyuan, a leading
Chinese scholar and a member of the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said education about science must be initiated from
childhood.
</P>
<P>
He condemned pseudo-scientific organizations like the illegal
Falun Gong sect, whose head Li Hongzhi calls himself the supreme
Buddha and has made illegal financial profits and gained political
fame among his followers.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Falun Gong is only the tip of an iceberg, Yu said,
noting that it could not be solved in one blow.
</P>
<P>
The series, containing articles written by many famous scholars
both at home and abroad, has been published to popularize science
and combat superstition.
</P>
<P>
China is currently carrying out a campaign to make the public
aware of the evils of Falun Gong, which has been found to be a
well-organized body and to have conducted many illegal activities
against the government.
</P>
<P>
Li Hongzhi, a former forest ranger, has told his followers that
the "doomsday is coming" and "no one but himself can save the
world." He has also ordered his followers not to go to doctors
when they fall ill.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, a large number of former Falun Gong
practitioners have quit the illegal organization, while the media,
police and local scientists, including doctors, have spared no
effort to give numerous pieces of evidence concerning the harm
done by Falun Gong, which has caused hundreds of deaths among its
practitioners.
</P>
<P>
In Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu Province, local
police have accused Li Hongzhi and his Beijing-based Falun Dafa
Research Society of masterminding the April 26 siege of the
provincial government compound by local Falun Gong practitioners.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 2,127, or more than 99 percent of local Falun Gong
practitioners in Lanzhou, have renounced the sect, according to
police sources. Of the 163 intellectual practitioners, 161 have
quit Falun Gong, the police said.
</P>
<P>
A report from east China's Jiangsu Province says that most
local retired officials have never believed in the Falun Gong cult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
