<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Remains of Nanjing Massacre Victims Uncovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The remains of 112 Nanjing
massacre victims have been found at an excavation site on the
premises of the Nanjing Jiangdongmen Museum since the end of last
month, according to the curator of the museum today.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Chengshan, the curator, said the remains, together with
those of 54 victims discovered near the same site last year, are
vivid evidence of the crimes committed by the Japanese invaders in
1937.
</P>
<P>
According to forensic identification, the remains include
skeletons of young men and women, elderly people and children.
There are nine skeletons of children, the youngest only three
years old. Many victims had been beheaded, and their bodies bore
evidence of wounds and other injuries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the burial places where the remains of 166 victims
have been found separately since last year are connected with each
other, covering about 420 sq m. At least 2,000 people are
estimated to have been buried in the area.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents reveal that the area around the
Jiangdongmen Museum was used as a killing ground when the Japanese
committed the massacre in December 1937. More than 10,000 people
were killed at that time.
</P>
<P>
To preserve the evidence, the Nanjing municipal government has
allocated money to build display rooms for the remains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
