<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots Visit Monastery in Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,000 Greek Cypriots
Sunday crossed into the northern Turkish Cypriots-controlled area
of Cyprus to visit the monastery of Saint Andreas on the
Assumption day, a very important day in the Orthodox calendar.
</P>
<P>
Many of them are elderly and young people who visited the
monastery for the first time to attend a church service held there.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Spokeswoman Sarah Russell said here that this is the 12th
such pilgrimage which the U.N. peace-keeping force in Cyprus
(UNFICYP) has helped to organize since 1995.
</P>
<P>
She said it is normal practice for the UNFICYP to provide
assistance to the Greek Cypriots to facilitate such visits.
</P>
<P>
The one-day trip started early in the morning when pilgrims
gathered at the Ledra Palace check point in Nicosia to board
buses. And they are due to return before dusk in the day.
</P>
<P>
The convoy of about 25 buses is accompanied by U.N. vehicles to
facilitate passage through the U.N.-controlled buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, Greek Cypriots paid several visits to
the northern Turkish Cypriot area on special religious days, such
as Easter Sunday or Assumption Day.
</P>
<P>
Similar trips were also arranged for Turkish Cypriots over the
past few years to visit places of worship in the southern area,
which is controlled by the Cyprus government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
