<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Dismisses Covert Election Bid Funding Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
's Office on Sunday denied the media reports that a millionaire
supporter gave the prime minister 250,000 pounds (400,000 U.S.
dollars) to help secure his 1997 general election leadership win.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Sunday Telegraph said former Treasury Minister
Geoffrey Robinson paid the money to fund Blair's private office
before the general election.
</P>
<P>
"It is laughable and ridiculous," the Reuters quoted a
spokesman for Blair as saying. But the spokesman declined to
comment further.
</P>
<P>
Robinson, who is still a member of parliament, was forced to
resign last year from the Treasury over a home loan of 373,000
pounds (596,800 dollars) to former Trade Secretary Peter Mandelson,
who also resigned last year after it emerged that he failed to
declare the loan.
</P>
<P>
Robinson is expected to expose Labor party funding in a
forthcoming autobiography in revenge for his own disgrace over the
Mandelson loan, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
