<HEADLINE> Antiwar Rallies Held to Mark Japan's Surrender in World War II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Several Japanese civic groups held
antiwar rallies in Tokyo Sunday on the 54th anniversary of Japan's
surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the rallies expressed their opposition to the
enactment of a set of bills to implement the updated Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation guidelines, moves in Japan to revise the
country's peaceful constitution and official visits to the
Yasukuni Shrine.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 people took part in a rally staged by the Japan
Peaceful Liaison Conference of Relatives of War Dead at an
assembly hall in central Tokyo on Sunday morning and shouted
slogans such as "Refuse to cooperate in war," "No revision to the
constitution".
</P>
<P>
Addressing the gathering, Okawa, head of the civic organization,
urged the Japanese government to remember the history of Japan's
past invasion to its neighboring Asian countries, and offer
sincere apology to people in those countries and make
compensations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at another rally at the Chitoribuchi graveyard for war
dead, opposition Social Democratic Party (SDP) chairwoman Takako
Doi criticized the government for enacting the bills related to
the new Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines, and warned that
Japan faces the danger to fall into the abyss of war if it
implements the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines call for more Japanese logistic support to U.
S. forces in emergency cases in "areas surrounding Japan". Critics,
however, argued that the guidelines could drag Japan into war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
