<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Military or Political Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since 1993, the U.N. has imposed sanctions on the UNITA,
including prohibition of its trade in diamond, the sale of
petroleum products and arms to the rebel movement, and freezing
UNITA's assets.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions also banned foreign travel by UNITA officials and
adult members of their families.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the U.N. committee overseeing the enforcement of
sanctions against the UNITA has enlisted the cooperation of a
broad coalition of interests, including the global diamond
industry, to enforce the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the committee, Robert Fowler, assured that the goal
in such broad diplomatic effort is to ensure that the UNITA goes
back to dialog in peacefully resolving the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Angolan ambassador to the United Nations,
Afonso van Dunem, said that his government has made a "positive
endorsement" for the U. N. presence in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
But the ambassador stressed that the Angolan government has
been in favor of a "not so big" U.N. presence, in correspondence
with the reality of the situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fightings are still going on between the Angolan
government troops and the UNITA rebels in many parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Considering U.N. as a shield for the UNITA, the Angolan
government demanded a pull-out of the U.N. observer mission in
Angola last January when the government troops encountered some
setbacks in battle-fields in the central provinces of Huambo and
Bie. The U.N. mission formally pulled out from the war-torn
country on March 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Now, the U.N. has expressed a will to maintain a mediatory
organization in Angola to facilitate the peace process in the
war-torn southern African country.
</P>
<P>
It is shocking, but true, that some Angolans have never known
peace in their country. The Angolan people as well as the whole
region are eager to see peace in the war-ravaged country as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has since his election been
promoting the idea of "culture of peace" instead of "culture of
arms". The 35th summit of the Organization of the African Unity
(OAU) in Algiers has set the year 2000 as the year of African
peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Against such a backdrop, the southern African leaders, who have
seen the conflicts in Angola and the DRC weakening not only
individual states but also regional efforts to achieve economic
growth and competitiveness, will be considering a fresh initiative
to resolve the Angolan conflict.
</P>
<P>
They, committed to acting in solidarity and resolving conflicts
in the region, will review the situation in Angola and will for
sure reach consensus to bring an early end to the Angolan civil
war which has been going on since 1975 with only some four years
of uneasy truce.
</P>
<P>
But observers here believe that the Angolan crisis will not be
resolved militarily but diplomatically through peaceful and
political means, though the regional leaders will probably back
their support for a peace agreement with the threat of military
force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Seizes Over 500 Kilograms of Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish gendarme soldiers have
seized 513.8 kilograms of heroin in an anti-drug operation in
eastern Turkey, an official statement said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the Turkish Gendarme Commandership,
said the gendarme soldiers on Friday stopped a truck in the
anti-drug operation in Agri province near neighboring Iran and
found the heroin in 25 bags and 498 parcels hidden in the secret
places of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The driver of the vehicle was arrested for alleged involvement
in the case, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The driver confessed that two Iranian drug smugglers gave him
10,000 Marks for bringing the heroin to Istanbul from Iran.
</P>
<P>
Turkish police conducted 2,928 operations against
drug-trafficking last year and seized over 10 tons of drugs,
including 5.3 tons of hashish and 3.8 tons of heroin.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is on a transit route of drugs from the border area of
Afghanistan and Pakistan to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
