<HEADLINE> Following are the highlights of the diplomatic news released by Xinhua today: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), met with a Japanese delegation of experts
on the afforestation in deserts here today.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, headed by Masayoshi Takemura, a member of the
House of Representatives of the Japanese Diet, is scheduled to
plant trees in deserts in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region,
together with Chinese volunteers.
</P>
<P>
Meeting the delegation, Buhe expressed his thanks to Takemura,
who devoted himself to Japan-China friendship and particularly to
the environmental protection cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The tree-planting program, initiated by both the Chinese and
Japanese sides today, the 54th anniversary of Japan's surrender in
World War II, will not only benefit the cause of environmental
protection, but also reflects the sincere desire for peace and
friendship of the people of the two countries, Buhe said.
</P>
<P>
First Chinese Group Ready for Australia Tour
</P>
<P>
The first group of Chinese tourists will leave here tomorrow
for Australia, beginning their eight-day tour of the country.
</P>
<P>
The China Travel Service (CTS) has organized the group,
consisting of 13 Beijing residents, in accordance with a tourism
treaty signed by the Chinese and Australian governments.
</P>
<P>
Australian Ambassador to China Richard Smith today hosted a
special ceremony to bid farewell to the tourists.
</P>
<P>
The first group is scheduled to visit Sydney, Melbourne and
Brisbane, among other places, CTS said.  
</P>
