<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Drums Up Support for Mbeki's Renaissance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Africa was still defined as a continent trapped in a spiral of
military coups and debt and haunted by poverty and fastest-growing
rate of HIV infection rate in the world.
</P>
<P>
There was a general feeling at the meeting that political
tension, civil strife, HIV/AIDS and poverty needed to be addressed
urgently if the renaissance vision was to be realized, sources
close to the meeting said on sunday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place behind close doors to prepare the
ground for the SADC summit slated for August 18.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, the heads of the 14 member states are
expected to sign protocols on trade, health, wildlife conservation
and law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Foreign Minister Nkosazana Zuma, who was
chairing the two-day foreign ministerial meeting, told delegates
that the gathering was convened at a crucial time in SADC's
history.
</P>
<P>
As these countries enter the new millennium, the question is
whether they are collectively ready to face the massive challenges
lying ahead.
</P>
<P>
These included globalization and the need to ensure that
southern AfrIca took charge of its destiny.
</P>
<P>
In ushering in the new millennium, regional governments should
vow to change Africa's image as a continent of war, civil strife,
ethnic tension, genocide and high levels of illiteracy, said Zuma.
</P>
<P>
"History has charged us with the responsibility of doing the
best we can for the benefit of our people. We therefore have to
act in solidarity and resolve areas of conflict before they play
themselves out in wars," she said.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that there were only four months left before the
next century, she said regional governments needed to consider
whether or not they were ready to pool their resources to effect
rapid socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
Southern Africa should commit itself to abandon war and strive
for peace and stability which, Zuma said, were both prerequisites
for development.
</P>
<P>
"Our people, particularly our children, deserve better. We
have to unleash the creative and innovative energies of our people
-- men and women as equals, including our youth and the disabled
-- for the development of society in our countries, the region and
the rest of the African continent" she said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that there were concerns at the meeting that
although some protocols had been ratified they had not yet been
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Some delegates called for realizing economic integration and
stimulating economic growth which remained a challenge for the
SADC, stressing that the cost of non-integration is unbearable and
undermines the social upliftment of African people.
</P>
<P>
The SADC states are Angola, Botswana, the Democratic Republic
of the Congo, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Mauritius, Namibia,
Seychelles, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
