<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Explore Tourism Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of Southern
African Development Community (SADC) discussed the possibility of
exploring tourism potential in the region at their just-concluded
meeting, sources close to the meeting said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers ended their two-day close-door meeting late
Saturday night to discuss a wide range of issues prior to a SADC
summit planned for August 18, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to political and military conflicts in the region,
the summit will also highlight economic issues, especially the
"sluggish" economic growth and projected food shortage in the
region, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
A report submitted to the meeting identified tourism as the key
economic drive for the region in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
According to the 48-page document drafted by the World Travel
and Tourism Council (WTTC), this ever-expanding service sector
offered SADC governments a new opportunity to boost economic
growth and accelerate job creation.
</P>
<P>
The WTTC urged southern African governments to make travel and
tourism a cabinet priority when formulating national policies on
education, employment, trade and investment, as well as in
strategies to encourage poverty alleviation, rural employment and
local government.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested that by 2010, tourism could provide some
650,000 jobs through southern Africa. Over 1.6 million jobs could
also be created directly and indirectly by travel demand across
the region's broad economy.
</P>
<P>
The report identified continuing conflict, political and
economic uncertainty in some SADC states as well as high profile
bombings and kidnappings, as impediments to the growth of the
tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
Other areas of concern included gaps in infrastructure, a lack
of capacity, the need for major investment in facilities and the
high amount of "red tape" both for companies doing business in
SADC countries and for potential visitors.
</P>
<P>
The report said that success in tourism lay in increased public
sector involvement in the development of an overall regional
marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, SADC was advised to implement studies in order
to assist member economies in identifying new market and product
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The report said the southern African countries should move
toward open and competitive markets. This could be achieved by
liberalizing trade, transport and telecommunications sectors.
</P>
<P>
For example, these governments would attract more scheduled and
 chartered air services if they opened up their transport markets,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Some countries, including South Africa, have said they
recognize the potential of this sector and its pushing for closer
cooperation in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
