<HEADLINE> SAARC Discussion on Rural Development Begins in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A SAARC sub-regional
discussion program on the promotion and development of
cooperatives and rural development institutions started here
Sunday, the official RSS new agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five people including senior officials from the central
banks of Nepal, India, Sri Lanka, Bhutan, the Maldives and
Bangladesh participated in the five-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the discussion program is to review the
role of cooperatives in rural development of the SAARC countries
-- Nepal, India, Sri Lanka, Bhutan, the Maldives, Bangladesh and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, organized by four Nepali banks and the National
Cooperatives Development Board, will also focus on identifying the
problems of financial institutions and cooperatives and looking
for alternative concepts for institutions involved in poverty
alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the program, Nepali Minister for Agriculture
Chakra Prasad Bastola said poverty alleviation has been a common
concern for all SAARC countries, pointing out that all countries
in SAARC are poor and Nepal even poorer than other SAARC
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that since agriculture is the sole source of livelihood
 for 80 percent of Nepalese, agricultural development is an
indispensable effort to bring them into the national mainstream.
</P>
<P>
"We have initiated programs for providing rural credits to
rural women through banks and we are already witnessing the
positive impact of these efforts," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have all made concerted efforts in the past to provide
subsidized fertilizers, seeds, irrigation and agricultural road
facilities to the rural people," Said Bastola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
