<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Moroccan foodstuff production accounted for 35 percent
of its domestic production of manufacturing industry last year to
reach 52 billion dirhams (5.3 billion U.S. dollars), said a report
released by the Moroccan Establishment of Contracting works.
</P>
<P>
The report indicates that exports of manufactured foodstuffs
have exceeded 700 million dollars, or about 19 percent of
Morocco's total industrial exports, the Arabic daily Al Hayat
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Food exports include canned vegetables and sea food, which
represent 43 percent of the total production.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia ranks the first among the Gulf
Cooperation Council states in the volume of joint industrial
investments, with 4.11 billion dollars in 24 industrial projects
by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic Alam Al Yom reported Sunday Bahrain came the second
with 2.754 billion dollars in 16 projects, followed by the United
Arab Emirates (UAE), the Sultanate of Oman, Qatar, Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The World Islamic Relief Authority in Saudi Arabia
has distributed 4,363 tons of dates among Muslims in 24 countries
in Asia, Africa and Europe, said Adnan Bin Khalil Pasha, secretary
general of the relief authority.
</P>
<P>
Local economic newspaper Iqtissadiya said Sunday that the
distribution was implemented under the instruction Saudi King Fahd
Bin Abdul Aziz with 14 million beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
The relief, valued at about 3.8 million dollars, went to 24
four countries, including Indonesia, Bangladesh, Pakistan,
Afghanistan, the Philippines, Sudan and Mauritania.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi coast guards foiled an attempt to smuggle 160
cartons of liquor to the country and arrested smugglers, the Saudi
Press Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The liquor was seized in the boat near the Khobar shore in
eastern Saudi Arabia, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
An official source in the Border Guard Department said Saturday
that Saudi coast guards followed the boat into Saudi territorial
waters when they learned that it carried liquor.
</P>
<P>
When the boat stopped at the northern shore of Khobar, the
guards searched it and found 2002 bottles of liquor in 160
cartons. 
</P>
