<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Military or Political Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Angola crisis, together with
the fragile Congo cease-fire, will be one major topic at the
coming summit of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
in Maputo next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It must have been one major issue grinding the minds of the
ministers of SADC member states at the just ended closed-door
meeting of the Council of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
What kind of solutions to the crisis will the ministers present
to the heads of state or government at the summit?
</P>
<P>
At the last SADC summit in Mauritius last September, the
regional leaders declared Angolan rebel movement UNITA chief Jonas
Savimbi a war criminal, "to be hunted down", but the political
will and the military means lagged behind.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, this matter has to be reconsidered, and the Maputo
summit would aim at a fresh political accord guaranteed by
regional governments.
</P>
<P>
At the Wednesday summit, there will be the political will to
resolve the conflict which has created some two million refugees
and even compounded the poverty situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
If the war carries on for a few more months, there may be
horrible stories of starvation, said an official with the U.N.
Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO). The World Food Program
(WFP) has also estimated that Angola currently needs some 13,000
tons of food aid each month.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos
might seek military help from its SADC neighbors to settle the
civil war with the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan authorities have issued an arrest warrant against
Savimbi on charges including rebellion, sabotage, murder and
torture.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe was said to be pressuring South Africa and other
countries in the region to agree at the summit to use military
force to back peace efforts in Angola.
</P>
<P>
According to some Zimbabwean officials, the cease-fire
agreement for the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), which
was signed in Zambian capital Lusaka on July 10 by the six
countries directly involved in the DRC conflict, represented "a
new vision for peace-keeping in Africa", which should be extended
to the Angolan context.
</P>
</TEXT>
