<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Find Connection Between Psychosis Chromosome Abnormality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese researchers
led by Feng Zhiying, the president of Tianjin's Anding Hospital,
have concluded that males with two X-chromosomes or females with
one X-chromosome are more likely to suffer from psychosis than
normal people.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the group began conducting research on 1,038 male and
1,746 female patients at the hospital who were suffering from
psychosis and found that a probability of the X-chromosome
abnormality of 3.2 percent for the male patients and 7.5 percent
for the female patients. The probability of X-chromosome
abnormality among normal men is 1 out of 1,500 and among normal
women 1 out of 5,000.
</P>
<P>
The research team also found from clinical studies that people
suffering from X-chromosome abnormalities have other symptoms like
slow brain and body development, incomplete growth of sperm or
ovaries, and sex gland disorders.
</P>
<P>
Professor Feng Zhiying suggests that people suffering from X-
chromosome abnormalities be given psychological adjustment at an
early age and supplementary treatment for improper glandular
secretions, as well as special education for the mentally retarded
to reduce the incidence of psychosis at an older age if they are
diagnosed with the abnormality when they are still young.
</P>
<P>
The real cause of psychosis is still unknown, but the disease
is commonly believed to be connected to heredity and environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
