<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Military or Political Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Earlier this year, presidents Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, Sam
Nujoma of Namibian and Laurent Kabila of the DRC met in Luanda and
formed an alliance with dos Santos against the UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state resolved to use "all possible measures" to
help dos Santos' government.
</P>
<P>
However, so far, "all possible measures" have excluded
Zimbabwean and Namibian military involvement because they already
have thousands of troops in the DRC, propping up Kabila's regime,
and the troops there are unlikely to be home before Christmas as
expected.
</P>
<P>
"A military deployment now by Zimbabwe is out of the question.
But there has to be that general consensus within the SADC on a
military commitment shared by all countries which would lighten
the burden," a diplomat based in Luanda said, adding that although
Angolan issue would be high on the agenda, there would be no
military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Military intervention is never going to happen, the diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
Boniface Chidyausika, Zimbabwe's outgoing ambassador to Angola,
also said that the diplomatic approach was the only way. "If there
is a common approach, a common position, it could be like Congo.
Intervention in Angola could be similar to that in Congo. But
diplomatically not militarily," he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, Zimbabwe has been trying to persuade
other SADC states, South Africa in particular, into getting
involved militarily on the side of Kabila in the DRC and dos
Santos' government in Angola.
</P>
<P>
But all the indications are that South Africa is understandably
 reluctant to fall into the kind of regional entrapment being
suggested by Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
South Africa sent peace-keeping troops to the DRC only after
the cease- fire was signed and would engage only in information
gathering.
</P>
<P>
Senior South African government officials dismissed the
Zimbabwean official's suggestion that a willingness was developing
among SADC member states to deploy military forces in Angola to
back up a new peace initiative there.
</P>
<P>
However, South African deputy foreign minister Aziz Pahad has
said that his government will continue to vigorously pursue the
agenda for peace and conflict resolution on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, the SADC would reinforce its efforts in Angola as the
United Nations has urged to enforce the sanctions against the
UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
Partly due to the non-effectiveness of the sanctions, the UNITA
rebels have raised an estimated three to four billion U.S. dollars
over the past eight years through diamond sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
