<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Tourism Still Booms Despite Currency Appreciation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's tourism industry
continued to grow in the first half of this year despite a 15
percent appreciation of its currency from the same period last
year, the Thai News Agency (TNA) said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tourism and related businesses earned the country up to 138
billion baht (3.7 billion U.S. dollars) in the first half of this
year, with foreign tourist arrivals rising to nearly 3.5 million,
TNA quoted Thai Farmers' Research Center, a leading research
institute of the country, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from East Asia outpaced those from western countries
in the first six months this year, with their arrivals reaching
2.44 million, an increase of 18 percent over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Economic revival in some East Asian countries and people there
changing behavior to travel to near and cheap destinations rather
than far away ones were reasons behind the surge, the research
center noted.
</P>
<P>
Overall foreign tourist arrivals are expected to reach 8.4
million, an 8.2 percent increase from last year, according to the
research center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
