<HEADLINE> State of Emergency Declared in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A month-long state of emergency
was declared by Russia's breakaway Chechnya republic on Sunday,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov's office said during the
state of emergency, which starts Monday, the troops will be put on
combat alert and stricter passage regime will be imposed along its
border with Dagestan, another Russian republic where federal
troops are routing Islamic militants that took several villages.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov's decision came after Russian acting Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin's indication Friday that rebel positions inside
Chechnya could also be bombed in the latest campaign against the
Islamic militants who infiltrated the Dagestani villages.
</P>
<P>
The armed gunmen are commanded by Chechen warlord Shamil
Basayev and Khattab, an Arab who is thought to be from Jordan or
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The militants seized the villages in the Botlikh district of
Dagestan, close to the border with Chechnya, on August 7.
</P>
<P>
Chechen authorities have repeatedly denied that they had
anything to do with the militants roaming the Dagestani villages.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with regional officials Friday in Tomsk, Siberia,
Putin said Russian troops would pound rebel positions wherever
possible, including inside Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"Chechnya - this is the territory of Russia, and we will strike
at militants wherever they are located," Putin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
