<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Catholic Youths Continue Violent Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Catholic youths continued with
sporadic acts of violence in Northern Ireland's second-largest
city of Londonderry early Sunday morning, hours after thousands of
Protestant Apprentice Boys marched through the city.
</P>
<P>
Under the cover of darkness, several vehicles were hijacked and
burnt, and one was used to ram a shopfront which was then set
alight. Several buildings, including three banks, were also badly
damaged by fire.
</P>
<P>
Police said most shops in the city center of Londonderry, known
as Derry to its Catholic majority, were looted.
</P>
<P>
Fire engines moved around the town, but there were no sign of
the clashes between police and demonstrators during the day
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A crowd of between two and three hundred people were said to
have gathered in the city center in the early hours of Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Police stayed out of the area for much of the night, but
officers in riot gear eventually moved in to clear the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's controversial parade, involving up to 10,000
Apprentice Boys and 150 bands, was held amid a huge security
presence.
</P>
<P>
Police succeeded in keeping apart the marchers and residents of
the city's mainly Catholic and nationalist Bogside area.
</P>
<P>
Petrol bomb attacks continued overnight. Nationalist youths
attacked the police throughout Saturday afternoon, while a number
of lorries were hijacked and burnt out, but the march itself
passed off peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The march in Londonderry followed violence in the Lower Ormeau
Road area of Northern Ireland capital Belfast on Saturday morning
when nationalists attempted to block the route of a smaller
Apprentice Boys parade.
</P>
<P>
Scuffles broke out as police wearing riot gear moved 200
demonstrators who were sitting in the road. Several people
suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
Parades by the Protestant Orange Order and the Apprentice Boys
have been the subject of controversy for many years in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The marchers view the parades as a traditional expression of
their culture, but in Catholic nationalist areas they are often
viewed as intimidating.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's parades commemorated the 1689 Siege of Derry, when
Protestant apprentices shut the gates of the walled city against
the forces of the Catholic King James II.
</P>
<P>
The Londonderry and Belfast parades were given the go-ahead by
the Northern Ireland Parades Commission.
</P>
<P>
The clashes in Londonderry happened as the people of Omagh
prepared to mark the first anniversary of the bombing of the town
which claimed 29 lives. It was the worst atrocity in more than 30
years of violence in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
