<HEADLINE> Thailand Ready to Implement First Anti-money Laundering Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Justice Ministry is
ready to implement its first money laundering control law which is
targeted to help the country fight drug trafficking and other
illicit transactions, Thailand News Agency (TNA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Suthas Ngernmuon was quoted by TNA as saying
that those who had laundered money in Thailand would find it very
hard to pick up a legal loophole to continue their illicit
operation after the new law takes effect.
</P>
<P>
He said the Office of the Anti-Money Laundering Committee would
be set up soon to facilitate the enforcement of the law.
</P>
<P>
The effectiveness of the new law would depend on the
cooperation of financial institutions which should examine the
accounts of their clients to trace any unusual transactions, said
the minister.
</P>
<P>
"If the law was implemented effectively, it would also help the
government suppress drug trafficking gangs," said Suthas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai Parliament President Wan Muhamad Nor Matha was
reported as saying that the authorities would be empowered to
check the financial records of money laundering suspects with the
implementation of the law.
</P>
<P>
The law requires financial institutions, land registration
offices and some other professions to report all transactions that
are unusual, suspicious or in excess of a given amount to the
Office of the Anti-Money Laundering Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
