<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Marks "National Mourning Day" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshis Sunday observed the
24th anniversary of the death of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, "the
Father of the Nation."
</P>
<P>
The day is officially observed as "National Mourning Day" since
1996, when the Awami League led by Sheikh Hasina, the eldest of
the two surviving daughters of Mujibur Rahman, came to power after
21 years.
</P>
<P>
In the early hours of the day in 1975, Mujibur Rahman and his
family members were killed by some disgruntled army officers, and
were survived only by his two daughters -- Sheikh Hasina, the
incumbent prime minister, and Sheikh Rehana, who happened to be
abroad during the killing.
</P>
<P>
Mujibur Rahman, born in March 1920, was the first prime
minister of independent Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Various programs were organized by political parties and other
organizations to mark the day, which was declared a public
holiday.
</P>
<P>
Early in the morning, President Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina placed wreaths at the portrait of Mujibur
Rahman at his residence in Dhanmondi in the city.
</P>
<P>
In a message issued on the occasion, the president said "His
life-long dedication and continuos struggle resulted in the birth
of an independent and sovereign Bangladesh through a... War of
Liberation."
</P>
<P>
"His tragic death... is a shameful chapter of our national
history," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on political parties to forget "political difference,
bitterness among ourselves and sorrows of the past in the great
interest of the nation," and to ensure "national advancement"
through unity and consensus by forgetting narrow party
affiliations.
</P>
<P>
In a separate message, Hasina urged "all the countrymen to take
a vow to work for building a happy and prosperous 'Sonar Bangla'
(prosperous Bangladesh)... by turning the grief... into strength."
</P>
<P>
"We shall have to be successful in the struggle for building a
country free from hunger, illiteracy and poverty, flourishing
democratic culture and establishment of rule of law," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
