<HEADLINE> Chittagong Port Authority Undertakes Development Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chittagong Port Authority
(CPA) of Bangladesh has undertaken development projects with a
total cost of 228 million U.S. dollars to enhance the country's
foreign trade activities through expansion of container handling
capacity of the port, according to press reports available here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong Port is the largest sea port, which is 224
kilometers southeast of here.
</P>
<P>
As part of the program, a 150-million-dollar container terminal
with a 1,000-meter-long berthing capacity will be built at the new
mooring area of the port, CPA sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Three feeder container vessels or two larger container vessels
and two to three general cargo vessels will be accommodated at the
berth.
</P>
<P>
Required back-up facilities for container handling will also be
constructed and container-handling equipment will be procured
under the self-financing project.
</P>
<P>
The consultant, yet to be appointed, will prepare the
specification and other details of the project, and BCEOM of
France and Mott McDonald of Britain are trying to get the
consultancy job.
</P>
<P>
The proposed project is scheduled to be implemented during the
current fiscal year and be completed in the 2004-2005 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The CPA will procure 142 pieces of container handling equipment
at a cost of 61 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The CPA would arrange the fund from its own resources and
procure the equipment through international tender if other
sources cannot be managed.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the CPA will also construct a 77,000 square meter
container yard at an estimated cost of 13 million dollars to be
funded from its own resources, and the project is scheduled to
commence in the current fiscal year and be completed in the
2001-2002 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
