<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serious Crimes Down in Second Quarter in Uganda: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Cases of serious crimes have
been in a downward trend in the second quarter of this year,
according to a report from the Ugandan police.
</P>
<P>
The six-page report from the Criminal Investigations Department
(CID) said that a total of 155 murder (not by shooting) cases were
recorded with 78 arrests in the second quarter compared with 395
murder cases leading to 271 arrests in the first three months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Murder induced by shooting, however, stood at 32 cases with
only 15 arrests, down from 103 cases and 37 arrests in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
From April to June, cases of defilement and related arrests
also showed drastic drop, the report said.
</P>
<P>
This declining trend was also reflected in armed and simple
robberies. There were 457 cases of armed robbery recorded in the
first quart and 175 arrests effected while in the second quarter
the figure went down to 193 cases with 86 arrests.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the plummeting of these serious crimes to
the raised public awareness and tightening up of security
measures.
</P>
<P>
However, the report warned that although serious crimes are
going down, they are still very rampant in the capital city of
Kampala and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
The police authorities would, as ever, take serious measures to
detect and weed out corrupt elements from the police force, the
report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
