<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Forces 5,000 Kenyans Flee to Uganda: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Drought in northwestern Kenya is
forcing thousands of farmers there into Uganda, with more than
5,000 already camped in hastily set-up villages.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Pokot tribesmen with their herds and families have
joined their Ugandan cousins across the border, Sunday's New
Vision quoted Moroto District Chairman Terrence Achia as saying
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kenyans joined their cousins in Karamoja, a
nomad tribe in northeastern Uganda famous for cattle rustling, in
search of food, grazing ground and water.
</P>
<P>
The tribemen in the exodus are camped in kraals (walled
villages) 80 km south of the main town of Moroto, itself 450 km
northeast of the capital city of Kampala.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was worried that the influx might result in
ethnic killings following the most recent one in which about 140
people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that 140 villagers were massacred on July 29 when
a Karamojong sub-tribe combined with Kenya's Turkana warriors
attacked their rival Bakora tribesmen.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan official said that the Pokot influx is scaring
people who are already traumatized by the recent killings and
called on the government to take security measures to avoid
occurrence of similar killings.
</P>
<P>
Spates of killings involving dozens in single incidents are
rife among the Karamojong who fight for cattle and grazing ground
between their rival sub-tribes, neighboring tribes and related
pastoralists from across the Kenyan border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
