<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Japanese Cabinet Members Visit Yasukuni Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Eight Japanese cabinet members
visited Tokyo's Yasukuni Shrine Sunday to pay respects to Japan's
war dead on the 54th anniversary of the country's surrender in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
The shrine houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war
criminals, including wartime prime minister Hideki Tojo, and some
2.4 million Japanese military personnel and officials who died
since 1853 in Japan's various wars.
</P>
<P>
The eight cabinet members included Transport Minister Jiro
Kawasaki, Labor Minister Akira Amari and Environment Agency chief
Kenji Manabe.
</P>
<P>
Their visits, plus that by Construction Minister Katsutsugu on
Tuesday, have brought to nine the total number of cabinet
ministers who have paid respects at the shrine this year, down
from 13 last year.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi has said that "taking the
current circumstances into consideration," he would not make a
similar visit. Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka also said he
would refrain from going to prevent "unnecessary misunderstanding.
"
</P>
<P>
Besides Obuchi and Nonaka, Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura,
Education Minister Akito Arima and six other ministers have
indicated they would not make a visit.
</P>
<P>
Japanese cabinet members' visits to the shrine, a bastion of
the wartime military government-sponsored Shintoism and symbol of
militarism in Japan before and during World War II, draw
widespread criticism from Japan's neighboring Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers' visits to the shrine are also controversial
as Japan's postwar Constitution stipulates separation of religion
and the State. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
