<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Issues Report on Student Rally Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme National Security
Council (SNSC) issued a report Saturday night on the rally of
Tehran University students last month and the following clashes
with police and civilian opponents in the dormitory.
</P>
<P>
The report said an investigation committee set up by SNSC
found the Tehran University dorm incident on July 8-9 is
"completely separate" from ensuing demonstrations and street riots.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred students staged a rally on July 8 at Tehran
University to protest the newly-approved Press Law and a ban on
the popular daily Salam (Hello), which supported moderate
President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Violence occurred after riot police forced into students'
dormitories without permission from the Interior Ministry. It was
the most violent clash since the 1979 Islamic revolution and
conservative plots were believed to be behind the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
No student was killed, the report said. But three people - a
civilian opponent, a police officer and a conscript of the Islamic
Revolution Guard Corps (IRGC) - were shot by bullets in the
incident. The conscript died in hospital.
</P>
<P>
The report said the probe committee believes that the law
enforcement forces had not pre-planned any confrontation with the
students and that there are no evidence indicating the chain of
command of law enforcement forces had made any earlier decisions
in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The report thus relieved senior commanders of the law
enforcement forces and special police and plainclothes of the
responsibility for the crackdown and blamed lower-ranking
officers, including a Tehran district commander, and civilian
opponents for fueling the violence.
</P>
<P>
More violent clashes erupted between riot police and thousands
of demonstrators protesting against the police crackdown on the
Tehran University students.
</P>
<P>
In defiance of a SNSC ban on illegal gatherings, several
groups of masked demonstrators armed with clubs and stones
clashed with rival groups, causing street riots, local reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The worsening situation prompted Khatami to call law and
order. "Any riot is against the interest of the Islamic system and
the nation as well as the government's slogans and policies,"
Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the president further stressed that violence,
tension and social, cultural and historical disintegration are
the worst enemies of political development and realization of a
civic society, economic growth and reforms.
</P>
<P>
The SNSC report seems aimed at calming down the situation,
further investigation is still underway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
