<HEADLINE> Export Credit Insurance Planned to Boost Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A specialized export credit
insurance company is under planning as a way to encourage China's
exports, the China Daily Business Weekly reports on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The idea of setting up such a company has been considered for
years and details of the preparatory work are now being discussed
by relevant government bodies, including the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation, the Ministry of Finance, China
Insurance Regulatory Commission, People's Insurance Company of
China and the Export and Import Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
The preparatory work may finish later this year, the report
said. It did not say when the company will be established.
</P>
<P>
A type of insurance typically backed by the government, the
export credit insurance covers economic losses resulted from
delayed importer's payments or debiting, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The insurance can help exporters increase credibility and its
accessibility to bank loans. It will also help boost exporter's
competitiveness by offering favorable and flexible payment
patterns. 
</P>
