<HEADLINE> Pepsi Production Line in Jordan Expected to Reopen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the Pepsi-Cola
Jordan branch expected their production line banned for
contamination last week to resume full production soon.
</P>
<P>
The officials described the ongoing meeting between the
Pepsi-Cola executives and the Jordanian Health Ministry as
positive and the ministry has approved recommendations for
improving the production procedures, Jordan Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry also dropped its threat to bring the local
Pepsi-Cola to trial, an unnamed Pepsi-Cola official was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The reusable bottling line of the Jordan Ice and Aerated Water
Company, a local bottling branch of Pepsi-Cola company of the
United States, was shut down last Tuesday after laboratory tests
showed they were contaminated with impurities, including sands,
insects and cement.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Ishaq Maraqa said Tuesday the plant`s
production of Miranda, Pepsi and 7UP will be banned for a week
before the bottler is taken to court.
</P>
<P>
He also hinted Tuesday the ban could be indefinite and would
not be lifted until the production line met the hygienic
standards set by his ministry.
</P>
<P>
Pepsi-Cola in reusable bottles are the flagship product of the
Pepsi company in the Jordanian market, accounting for some 80
percent of its overall operations in the kingdom with 20 million
cases each year.
</P>
<P>
Other production lines for canisters and plastic bottles were
not closed since the decision only covered glass bottles, Jordan
Times said.
</P>
<P>
The semi-closure came at the peak sales season for the soft
drink manufacturer with an influx of tourists and increased local
consumption.
</P>
<P>
However, local Pepsi-Cola officials refused to estimated the
potential losses which might be inflicted by the temporary ban.
</P>
<P>
Pepsi-Cola products accounted for some 75 percent of the
soft drinks market in Jordan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
