<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Orders Army Preparation for Implementing Wye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak has instructed the army to begin preparations for resuming
implementation of the Wye Memorandum on September 1, Israel Radio
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister and Defense Minister Ehud Barak has told the
IDF (Israeli Defense Forces) to prepare to put in motion the
implementation of the Wye agreement at the beginning of September
1999. This means the land handover will begin on October 1," the
radio quoted a statement issued by the prime minister's office
late Saturday night as saying.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, the other issues outstanding between the
two sides regarding Wye will be discussed," the statement said,
referring to such matters as the opening of a Palestinian seaport
in Gaza and a safe passage route linking Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
This announcement was actually a reiteration of Barak's
proposal on the timetable of restarting the Wye interim accord,
signed with the Palestinians by his hard-line predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu last October.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu froze the agreement, which calls on Israel to hand
over another 13 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians,
after carrying out the first of its three stages.
</P>
<P>
Ousting Netanyahu in the May election, Barak has promised to
implement the remaining stages of Wye, but proposed some changes
including folding the final stage into the final-status talks,
which deal with thorny issues like Jerusalem and Jewish
settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have reluctantly accepted his proposal to
restart the Wye agreement on the beginning of September and begin
to carry out the second stage of troop withdrawal on October 1.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides have been at odds over Barak's suggestion to
postpone the implementation of the third stage until February
2000, when the final-status talks are supposed to have been well
under way.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that the third stage be carried out by
mid-November in line with the original timetable of Wye.
</P>
<P>
Barak's envoy Gilad Sher and senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat met in Jerusalem Saturday night, for the second time
in three days, to continue their effort to resolve the difference
on the timetable for the Wye implementation.
</P>
<P>
Barak and Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
will hold a summit early in the week if the two negotiators reach
agreement on a timetable, Israel Radio reported. The Palestinians
have denied that such a summit has been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Sher and Erekat made no progress in their latest talks, but
promised to meet again Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Barak talked twice with U.S. President Bill Clinton
on the phone to discuss the latest developments in the peace
process and the upcoming visit to the region by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Albright originally scheduled her visit in mid-August with an
aim of ensuring the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks are on the
track and restarting the frozen negotiations between Israel and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
But she has postponed the visit by two weeks at the request of
Barak, who wants Washington to give him more time to iron out his
dispute with Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
