<HEADLINE> Zambian Buses Banned Night Movement: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police will ban night
movement of public transport vehicles, especially buses, on long
distance routes in a bid to curb road accidents.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Alex Chilufya said that when the ban is
effected, drivers would have to wait until daybreak to ferry
passengers.
</P>
<P>
He said police check-points along all major highways would be
used to detain vehicles whose drivers flout the regulation.
</P>
<P>
The police is empowered by law to take preventive measures
toward preservation of life, the spokesman was quoted by Sunday
Mail newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chilufya was speaking in the wake of last weekend's bus tragedy
in which 18 people, most of them school children, died.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred on the Great North Road near capital
Lusaka when the bus in which they were travelling rammed into a
stationary truck at about 19:30 hours.
</P>
<P>
Chilufya said that the Police Service was concerned about road
carnage and would do everything possible to ensure that people's
lives were protected.
</P>
<P>
He also called upon the Road Traffic Commission to compliment
police efforts by mounting road blocks in various areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
