<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slum Dwellers Coming Back to Bangladeshi Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Some slum dwellers, who were
earlier evicted by law-enforcing members, have started to return
to their respective places in Dhaka on hearing the news that the
High Court had ordered the government not to evict the slum
dwellers till August 19.
</P>
<P>
They have already started building thatched houses afresh at
their respective places in the capital city, The New Nation
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The slum people, along with the newcomers, were seen taking
shelters at different city slums where slums were demolished
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's High Court last Thursday directed the government
not to remove any more slums in the capital city till August 19
when the court resumes hearing of a writ petition challenging the
eviction of slums.
</P>
<P>
The writ petition, filed by three non-governmental
organizations and two slum dwellers, challenged the legality and
authority of the demolition of slums in Dhaka and the eviction of
inhabitants without arranging alternative accommodation and
without any prior notice.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day eviction drive beginning last Sunday,
members of the law-enforcing agencies dismantled about 10,000
shanties, rendering over 60,000 poor people homeless.
</P>
<P>
Estimates show that there are around 2 million slum dwellers in
Dhaka, which has a population of about 9 million.
</P>
<P>
A section of the slum dwellers under the patronage of some
godfathers were involved in drug and arms trafficking, and the
eviction drive was aimed at cutting crime and criminal activities,
according to police.
</P>
<P>
The Home Ministry directed the law-enforcing agencies to evict
the slums following the killing of a police constable in the city
early this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
