<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Reiterates Remorse for Asian War Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi expressed "deep remorse" once again on Sunday for Japan's
wartime acts in Asia while extending condolences to war victims in
neighboring Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
"That war caused tremendous pain and sorrow not only to our
country but also to people in many countries, particularly those
in neighboring Asian countries. We would like to express our deep
regret and condolences to them sincerely," Obuchi said at a
government-sponsored ceremony marking the 54th anniversary of
Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
Over the past seven years, Japan's prime ministers have made
similar remarks concerning Asian war victims at the annual event.
It was the second time for Obuchi to address such a ceremony since
he took office last July.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi meanwhile stressed the importance of building a
permanent peace.
</P>
<P>
"It is our important obligation to look back at the past with
sincerity, to pass onto the younger generation knowledge of the
sacrifices of the war dead as well as to build a permanent peace
so as to avoid a recurrence of the disaster of a terrible war,"
Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko, some 6,000
relatives of the Japanese war dead and about 1,000 government
officials and lawmakers attended the ceremony held at Nippon
Budokan hall in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the ceremony offered a minute of silent prayer
at noon for souls of the 3.1 million Japanese who died in the war.
</P>
<P>
In a brief memorial address delivered after the prayer, Emperor
Akihito also offered condolences to the war dead and prayed for
world peace.  
</P>
</TEXT>
