<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Says Indian Economy Strong Despite Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Caretaker Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee said on Sunday that the Indian economy has emerged
strong despite the recent armed conflict with Pakistan in Kashmir
and economic sanctions imposed on it following its nuclear tests
in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation on India's Independence Day here,
Vajpayee said economic growth increased to six percent and
inflation went down to an unprecedented 17-year low of around 1.19
percent.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural production hit an all-time high of over 200
million tons in 1998-99 and the foreign exchange reserves exceeds
over 30 billion U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said the economic sanctions against his country had
lost their effect and become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
In his 26-minute speech, Vajpayee ruled out resumption of
stalled bilateral talks with Pakistan on the ground that Islamabad
continued support for cross-border terrorism.
</P>
<P>
India would not allow Pakistan to succeed in its "designs" to
foment trouble in India and would take all steps to safeguard
security of the country, he told his countrymen from the ramparts
of the heavily-guarded historic Fed Fort in the capital.
</P>
<P>
He described his Lahore bus diplomacy last February as "a well
thought out and planned step" and accused Pakistan of having
"grounded the bus" by violating the Lahore pact in the conflict in
Kargil. 
</P>
