<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Updates with results George Bush Wins U.S. Republican Straw Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- George W. Bush, State
Governor of Texas, won the Iowa straw poll held on Saturday, which
was deemed as the first test to the U.S. Republican contenders for
the 2000 presidency.
</P>
<P>
Bush, also son of former President George Bush, achieved the
upper hand by pocketing 7,418 votes, followed by Steve Forbes and
Elithebeth Dole with 4,921 votes and 3,410 votes respectively,
said the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
"We won the vote," said Bush, who sought to solidify his front-
runner status through the informal poll." The winner is not George
W. Bush. It's the Republican Party and great ideas."
</P>
<P>
Republican Party officials said 24,500 people cast the ballots
on the campus of Iowa State University, twice as many as expected.
</P>
<P>
Many participants traveled aboard air-conditioned buses by
courtesy of the candidates, who also lured them with free food and
entertainment, and picked up the tab for the 25 dollars tickets
needed to vote.
</P>
<P>
Bush aides said they had purchased nearly 11,000 ballots and
distributed most of them to supporters.
</P>
<P>
Bush has budgeted 750,000 dollars for the contest while Steve
Forbes, a publishing giant and multimillionaire, reportedly spent
two million dollars on the event.
</P>
<P>
The straw poll is a fund-raiser for the Iowa Republican party,
as well as a political circus. Advocates say it helps provide an
assessment of a candidate's public appeal and the ability of his
organization to get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
Though no straw poll winner ever has won the Republican
nomination for the presidency, the contest could reshape the
Republican presidential field ahead of the first real votes for
nomination, the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
Besides Bush and Forbes, the contenders are Tennessee Governor
Lamar Alexander, President of Family Research Council Gary Bauer,
former President of American Red Cross Elizabeth Dole, radio talk
show host Alan Keyes, Senator Orrin Hatch, former vice president
Dan Quayle, TV commentator Pat Puchanan.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator John McCain has called the straw poll a "
scam and a "sham" and boycotted it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
