<HEADLINE> More People Keep Money at Private Banks in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- More and more people in Myanmar
are keeping money at the Asia Wealth Bank (AWB), one of the
leading private banks in the country, bringing about cash deposits
at the bank amounting to 58 billion Kyats (193.3 million U.S.
dollars) by mid-July, the New Light of Myanmar reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The bank had also given out loans totaling 26 billion Kyats
(86.6 million dollars) by that time, it said.
</P>
<P>
The deposits at the bank were obtained especially through the
introduction of the call deposit system and the safe deposit
locker system since October 1997 after the Asian financial crisis
started to hit Southeast Asia including Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The call deposit system is reported to have drawn over 2
billion Kyats (6.6 million dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
The AWB, with a total number of 28 branches across the country,
was first established with a capital of 60 million Kyats (200,000
dollars) and 84 staff members.
</P>
<P>
There are 19 private banks in Myanmar with the AWB, the Yoma
and the Myanmar Mayflower Bank leading in domestic commercial
banking services. The latter two respectively have 28 and 11
branches in the country.
</P>
<P>
The private banks in Myanmar hold about 45 percent of savings
deposits of the banking sector, while their loans account for
about 48 percent of the sector's loans to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
There are three state-owned banks in the country, including the
Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar started adopting the market-oriented economic policy in
late 1988 and reformed its banking system in 1990, allowing
private banks to operate again after they were nationalized in
1963. 
</P>
</TEXT>
