<HEADLINE> Warring Groups in Indonesia's Batam Sign Peace Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the warring groups
and tribes involved in a recent mass clash in Batam, Indonesia,
signed a peace pact on Saturday night and slaughtered goats, pigs
and carabao, marking the end of their conflict, Antara news agency
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
They declared that the two groups made assurances there would
no more unrest and they also agreed to disperse all field actions.
They guaranteed a peaceful situation in the city and that they
would hold a meeting to create pace.
</P>
<P>
The pact was signed by Benny Panjaitan and Rofinus Lorens and
was witnessed by local officials of the Batam municipality, Batam
Autonomy Region, and Commander of the Batam District Military
Command Lt. Col. Yul Aviandi, Chief of the Barelang Batam Police
Lt. Col. IGM Wibawa and some 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
A member of the National Commission for Human Rights, Bambang
W. Soeharto who attended the function, said the step taken by the
Batam administration to settle the rift between the two tribes
could be followed in similar cases in other regions of the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Such a step is a very good one and could be a model for
others," he was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
The riots occurred in Batam last month following a dispute over
parking lots between two individuals from the two communities. The
riots left 21 people dead and dozens injured.
</P>
<P>
Batam, just 35 km southeast of Singapore, is a special
industrial zone and also a popular tourist destination for
Singaporeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
