<HEADLINE> U.S. Republican Party Holds Straw Poll in Iowa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican contenders
for the 2000 presidency competed with each other Saturday in the
Iowa straw poll, the first test on the road to the White House.
</P>
<P>
George W. Bush, son of former President George Bush and State
Governor of Texas, was the heavy favorite to win the informal poll
when votes were counted at 0200 GMT on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here to win," said Bush, who sought to solidify his front-
runner status through the informal poll.
</P>
<P>
Republican Party officials estimated that 24,000 people were
present at the campus of Iowa State University to vote, twice as
many as expected.
</P>
<P>
Many participants traveled aboard air-conditioned buses by
courtesy of the candidates, who also lured them with free food and
entertainment, and picked up the tab for the 25-dollar-tickets
needed for the vote.
</P>
<P>
Bush aides said they had purchased nearly 11,000 ballots and
distributed most of them to supporters.
</P>
<P>
Bush has budgeted 750,000 dollars for the contest while Steve
Forbes, a publishing giant and multimillionaire, reportedly spent
two million dollars on the event.
</P>
<P>
The straw poll is a fund-raiser for the Iowa Republican party,
as well as a political circus. Advocates say it helps provide an
assessment of a candidate's public appeal and the ability of his
organization to get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
Though no straw poll winner ever has won the Republican
nomination for the presidency, the contest could reshape the
Republican presidential field ahead of the first real votes for
nomination, the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
Besides Bush and Forbes, other contenders included Tennessee
Governor Lamar Alexander, President of Family Research Council
Gary Bauer, former President of American Red Cross Elizabeth Dole,
radio talk show host Alan Keyes, Senator Orrin Hatch, former vice
president Dan Quayle, TV commentator Pat Puchanan.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator John McCain has called the straw poll a "
scam" and a "sham" and boycotted it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
