<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: All-round Development of Sino-Malaysian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad left here Sunday for a working visit to China
from August 18 to 20 via Khabarovsk, Russia, in conjunction with
the 25th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's visit to China at the invitation of his Chinese
counterpart Zhu Rongji is expected not only to further enhance
diplomatic relations but also produce more joint-venture projects,
Malaysian Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is scheduled to call on President Jiang Zemin and hold
an official meeting with Zhu to discuss bilateral issues
especially trade and investment. He is also scheduled to deliver
an address entitled "Malaysia-China Relations: Challenges and
Opportunities in the 21st Century" at the third Malaysia-China
Forum in Beijing on August 19.
</P>
<P>
The friendly relations between China and Malaysia have deepened
since the establishment of diplomatic relations. In recent years
in particular, contacts and cooperation between the two countries
have expanded at various levels, through different channels and in
all fields -- political, economic, cultural, educational, defense
and other areas.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations have grown from strength to strength as
the top leaders of the two countries have shown their political
will and pledged to forge mutually beneficial cooperation based on
the principles of mutual respect for each other's sovereignty and
territorial integrity, non-interference in each other's internal
affairs and peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of both sides have maintained close and frequent
contacts and exchanged visits which have brought about an
environment of harmony and amity and served to cement bonds of
friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's current visit is his fifth to China in his capacity
as the Malaysian prime minister. His first visit to China was in
November 1985, the second in June 1993, the third in May 1994 and
the fourth in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the same token, top Chinese leaders who visited Malaysia
include Chinese President Jiang Zemin in 1994 who also came to
attend the APEC leaders' informal meeting in Kuala Lumpur in 1997
and the East Asian leaders' informal consultation in 1998, Zhu
Rongji (then vice premier) in 1996, Li Peng (then premier) in 1990
and Yang Shangkun (former president) in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Economically, trade and investment between the two countries
have been on an upswing in recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, total trade between China and
Malaysia last year stood at 4.264 billion U.S. dollars, a 20-fold
increase over that in the early years of the establishment of
bilateral diplomatic relations. During the first half of this
year, total trade between the two countries reached 2.2958 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
For mutual investment, more than 140 Malaysian companies
including over 60 listed companies are registered in China, who
formed more than 140 joint ventures valued at more than 332
million U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Almost a similar number of Chinese companies formed joint
ventures in Malaysia. In addition, China is actively studying the
possibility of entering joint ventures in Malaysia to undertake
railway and power station projects and hi-tech projects.
</P>
<P>
A joint venture with investment worth more than 1 billion U.S.
dollars in pulp and paper production in Malaysia is at the final
stage of negotiation. The joint venture is expected to be
discussed during Mahathir's visit.
</P>
<P>
The fruitful economic cooperation between China and Malaysia is
guided by a number of agreements signed including the Agreement on
Avoidance of Double Taxation (1985), the Shipping Agreement
(1988), the Trade Agreement (1988), the Investment Protection
Agreement (1988), the Air Services Agreement (1988), the
Memorandum of Understanding on Information Cooperation (1992) and
the Agreement on Cooperation in Science and Technology (1992).
</P>
<P>
Bilateral cooperation in other fields such as culture,
education and sports has also developed steadily. The two
countries signed the Sports Agreement in 1993 and the Memorandum
of Understanding on Education Cooperation in 1997. More and more
Chinese students are coming to Malaysia for studies.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the people-to-people contacts keep the momentum of
increasing. According to Malaysian officials, in 1998, the number
of tourists from China increased to 275,150 from 232,957 in 1997
and during the first quarter of 1999, Chinese tourists increased
89.4 percent compared with the same period last year. And a larger
number of Malaysians are visiting China every year.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid told a local Chinese-language newspaper in a recent
interview that the Malaysian-Chinese relations are entering an era
of all-round development.
</P>
<P>
To bring Sino-Malaysian relations to new heights, the two
countries signed in Beijing in May this year the Joint Statement
on the Framework for Future Bilateral Cooperation, setting the
direction of development of the bilateral relations in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's fifth visit to China will surely further contribute
to cementing the bilateral ties between China and Malaysia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
