<HEADLINE> World Coffee Price to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The world's coffee producers
are expected to face a price crisis in the upcoming years,
business sources were quoted as saying on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This will be a result of supply outrunning demand, said Carlos
Alfaro Ruiz, vice president of Costa Rican Coffee Exporters
Chamber (CEC).
</P>
<P>
Alfaro said that the origin of this crisis could be traced back
to the cold spell occurring in Brazil in 1994, which forced the
world's biggest coffee producer to renew all its planting.
</P>
<P>
He said Brazil is expected to have the biggest coffee output in
history, probably 40 million 60-kilo bags, if no disrupting
natural factors occur.
</P>
<P>
A good harvest of coffee is also in sight for Costa Rica in the
present 1999-2000 season, of some 3.6 million bags, or a 10
percent to 12 percent increase over the previous harvest.
</P>
<P>
As a result, coffee supply will surpass world demand by 10
million bags, which may led to a fall in the price. The demand on
world market is estimated at 100 million bags.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Costa Rican coffee exports had diminished to
only 193 million U.S. dollars in the first half of this year, down
by 31.5 percent from the same period of 1998. The reduction was
attributed to a drop in the coffee price on world market, which
had varied between 92 and 97 dollars per quintal (46 kilos).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
