<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Confirms Forced Displacement in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
confirmed that the ruling Taliban militia are forcing tens of
thousands of people to displace from the Shamali valley near the
front lines north of the Afghan capital of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here late Saturday, the U.N. said
over 1,870 displaced families, or some 10,000 people, have entered
Kabul within a period of less than 36 hours on August 13-14,
adding that a major influx is anticipated within the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has obtained first-hand accounts from the new arrivals
representing all ethnic groups which verify that Taliban fighters
forced people out of their houses and told them to walk to the
Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
They also confirmed earlier reports that the Taliban are
intentionally setting homes on fire, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Some people said whole villages were burned to the ground and
crops set on fire to deter them from moving back to the
once-fertile valley.
</P>
<P>
Taliban authorities have continued to deny any "scorched earth"
policy in the area as reported.
</P>
<P>
International agencies in Kabul are monitoring the arrival of
growing numbers of the displaced people from the Shamali valley,
drawing up lists of the displaced, and providing new arrivals with
water and high protein biscuits.
</P>
<P>
Some of the displaced have made the 40-km journey on foot,
while others have been conveyed in trucks commandeered by Taliban
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Many of the new arrivals are not only dehydrated from their
journey but also are completely destitute and have only what they
were able to carry from their homes, according the U.N. press
release.
</P>
<P>
"Forced displacement and intentional destruction of civilian
houses are clear violations of international humanitarian law,"
said the press release.
</P>
<P>
It is also against the stated policy of the Taliban, whose
leader Mullah Omar earlier condemned such acts and called on
Taliban troops to respect the lives and property of civilians, the
press release noted.
</P>
<P>
International aid workers also reported another sizable
movement of civilians north of the front lines into the Panjsher
valley, the stronghold of the opposition forces led by former
defense minister Ahmad Shah Masood.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is concerned for their immediate welfare,
given the terrain and limits on access to the valley, said the
press release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
