<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Bids Farewell to Slain Journalist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands
of Bogota residents gathered on Saturday afternoon in the center
of the capital to hold a funeral ceremony for the slain journalist
Jaime Garzon.
</P>
<P>
The crowd, coming from all directions of the city and carrying
posters and white papers reading "No More Violence", gathered in
the Plaza of Bolivar, where also stood the Capitol of the Republic,
to bid farewell to Garzon, also a satirist and peace fighter.
</P>
<P>
Bishop Hector Gutierrez who was a teacher of the assassinated
reporter, said at the massive funeral that "Jaime has fought for a
better and different Colombia. We, who still are alive, must
continue striving for peace in Colombia."
</P>
<P>
"We will not accept the continuation of the violence in
Colombia," Jaime's sister Marison Garson said. "With the efforts
of all Colombians, starting with the political leaders, we will
turn the page in the 21st century, which will be a century of
peace."
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old journalist, also a comic and political activist,
was shot dead at 05:45 local time on Friday by two gunmen when he
was driving his jeep to his work.
</P>
<P>
Garzon's killing was Colombia's most striking assassination
since 1995 when gunmen, allegedly former members of the army's
secret service, killed Conservative Party leader Alvaro Gomez.
</P>
<P>
Garzon was the latest victim of Colombia's three-decade-long
civil conflict that has claimed more than 35,000 lives in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The crowd of mourners chanted slogans demanding an end to 35
years of violence in which both right-wing paramilitary militias
and leftist rebels regularly target civilians they accused of
collaborating with their enemies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
