<HEADLINE> Peru, Ecuador Satisfied With Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian Foreign Ministry
Saturday published a joint communique, signed by visiting
Ecuadorian President Jamil Mahuad and his Peruvian counterpart
Alberto Fujimori, which expressed satisfaction over their
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
In the document, the two presidents recognized the important
progress in the implementation of the Brasilia Accord, which was
singed in October of 1998. The accord went into effect on May 13,
1999 and ended a long-standing border dispute between the two
countries that erupted into wars in 1941, 1985 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the treaty has helped consolidate a new
neighborhood based on peace, friendship, cooperation, and
bilateral integration.
</P>
<P>
They also spoke highly of the Peruvian-Ecuadoran Neighborhood
Commission presided over by the foreign ministers, saying it
functions as a political mechanism to promote, support, and
coordinate the programs, projects and activities that require
close cooperation between Peru and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
They hailed the cooperation between the two countries in
identifying the exact location of the Centers of Commerce and
Navigation in the Saramiriza and Pijuayal localities.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori and Mahuad, who was on a state visit to Peru on August
11-13, announced that their countries will contribute five million
U.S. dollars each to the Binational Fund for Peace and Development,
praising the progress in the improvement of the diverse projects
that form the Binational Plan for the Development of the Border
Region.
</P>
<P>
Peru and Ecuador have signed the Document of Execution of the
Acceleration and Deepening Agreement on Free Trade, the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents reaffirmed the political will of their
governments to solve the problems and remove the barriers that
thwart a bigger growth and the diversification of bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
They instructed their respective foreign ministers to jointly
establish as soon as possible a mechanism for the tasks of
inspection, repairing, and replacement of markers in the shared
border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
