<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Expects to Enter CBI Before 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua expects to be included
in the Caribbean Basin Initiative (CBI) this year, which would
reduce the customs tariffs on several Nicaraguan products exported
to the United States, the La Prensa daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan ambassador in Washington Francisco Aguirre Sacasa,
quoted by the newspaper, said that there is strong opposition from
U.S. labor unions, an important group of political pressure, to
give trade benefits to countries whose products compete with U.S.
products.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat said that the United States is the main trade
partner of Nicaragua and its first supplier of economic aid.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries amounted to 455 million U.S.
dollars in 1998, with a surplus of 120 million dollars in favor of
Nicaragua. 
