<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Leaves for Visits to China, Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad left here Sunday for his fifth visit to China,
via Russia's Khabarovsk.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's visit, at the invitation of Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji, is in conjunction with the 25th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic relations between China and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit starting from August 18, Mahathir is
scheduled to call on President Jiang Zemin and hold an official
meeting with Premier Zhu to discuss bilateral issues especially on
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is expected to state Malaysia's stand on the "One
China" policy besides exchanging views with Zhu on the economic
crisis faced by the region, Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar said
earlier when announcing Mahathir's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir will also deliver an address at the Malaysia-China
Forum organized by the Asian Strategic and Leadership Institute
and host a dinner to celebrate the 25th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic relations between China and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid believed that the visit would further enhance
diplomatic relations and also result in more joint-venture
projects between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Among the joint ventures to be discussed is the setting up of
the Proton (Malaysia's national car manufacturer) plant in one of
the provinces in China, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
China on the other hand is keen to set up a pulp and paper
factory in Sabah, East Malaysia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Before his arrival in Beijing on August 18, Mahathir will stay
in Khabarovsk for three days. After his visit to China, he will
then visit Buryatia, Russia from August 20 to 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
