<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Rejects Ecuadorian Fruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Colombia has closed
its common border with Ecuador on allegation of a plague of
bananas, local press reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The closing of the border, which began on Wednesday, has
interrupted bilateral trade across the Rumichaca International
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
Colombian Agriculture and Livestock Institute (ICA) has
restricted the entry into the country of mangoes, bananas, guavas,
avocados, peaches, apples, grapes, plums, oranges, lemons, papayas
and other fruits from Ecuador, Brazil and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
An Ecuadorian Foreign Trade Ministry official was quoted by
press reports as saying on Saturday that Colombia's attitude had
much worried his country since it went against the economic
integration process.
</P>
<P>
Colombia is Ecuador's second biggest trade partner after the
United States. The annual Colombian-Ecuadoran trade volume amounts
to 1 billion U.S. dollars, with a surplus enjoyed by Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The common border of the two countries had previously been the
focus of Colombia's fight against Ecuadorian rice and spirits
which were banned for diverse phytosanitary reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
