<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Ecuador Continue Joint Naval Maneuvers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Ecuadorian and U.S. navies
continued their Unitas naval maneuvers Saturday in the port of San
Lorenzo, bordering with Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's exercises, in which a total of 1,500 Ecuadorian
military personnel and 1,500 soldiers from the United States took
part, included for the first time amphibious and surface ships
operations in the sea, the Ecuadorian Navy General Command in
Quito announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The naval forces of the two countries will also perform coastal
exercises that include day and night movements of troops in San
Lorenzo.
</P>
<P>
The Ecuadorian military authorities assured that the maneuvers
are not a military action against the guerrillas in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Residents of San Lorenzo and other nearby communities expressed
surprise for the presence of foreign troops, whom they see in the
Ecuadorian sea area with a large amount of equipment.
</P>
<P>
The Unitas naval maneuvers started on August 13 and was
scheduled to end on August 22. The U.S. Navy No. 30 Force
contributes a total of 2,178 military personnel and six ships in
the maneuvers, including a frigate, a destroyer, a searching ship,
a landing ship, a Coast Guard cutter and a nuclear submarine,
while Ecuador participates with a submarine and four ships.
</P>
<P>
Initiated in 1960 by U.S. Admiral Arleigh A. Burke, the Unitas
maneuvers have been held jointly by the navies of the United
States and several Latin American countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
