<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China voiced its strong resentment and firm opposition with
the U.S. government for allowing the Dalai Lama to visit the
United States, China's Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is an inalienable part of China, and the Tibet issue is
entirely China's internal affairs, which brooks no interference
from any foreign country, Zhu said, adding that the Dalai lama is
not merely a religious figure but a political exile engaged in the
activities of splitting China.
</P>
<P>
-- China's Vice-Premier Li Lanqing called for further efforts
to implement policies of medicare reform and set up a macro
population control system in line with the socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee,
made the remarks Saturday when meeting with representatives from
the country's medical sphere at Beidaihe, a summer beach retreat
in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Investigations here shows that Yao Jie, Li Xiaomei and Li
Xiaobing, key members of the outlawed "Falun Dafa Research Society
" in Beijing, earned more than 1.5 million yuan in two years
selling illegal publications to practitioners, according to
Beijing's public security and press and publishing departments.
</P>
<P>
-- The '99 Beijing International Tourist Culture Festival is
scheduled for September 5.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China will build more subways in large cities each with a
population of more than one million, beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
Subway lines already proposed total 430 kilometers in length,
requiring estimated investments of 140 billion yuan (16.8 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
-- China's building materials industry is expected to provide
numerous opportunities for overseas investment over the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Building Materials Industry will
announce 69 projects involving a total investment of 15.78 billion
yuan (1.9 billion U.S. dollars) for overseas investment during the
Third China Fair for International Investment and Trade to be held
in Xiamen in east China's Fujian Province from September 8-12.
</P>
</TEXT>
