<HEADLINE> Cooper, Four Others Added to USA Basketball Women's Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Two-time WNBA MVP Cynthia
Cooper and Chamique Holdsclaw were among the five players
officially added today to the 10-member 1999-2000 USA Basektball
National Team.
</P>
<P>
Last August, USA Basketball selected forward-center Lisa Leslie
of the Los Angeles Sparks, and guards Ruthie Bolton-Holifield of
the Sacramento Monarchs, Nikkis McCray of the Washington Mystics,
Dawn Staley of the Charlotte Sting and Katie Smith of the
Minnesota Lynx as its five core members.
</P>
<P>
Today, USA Basketball named Cooper of the Houston Comets,
forwards Holdsclaw of Washington, Yolanda Griffith of Sacramento
and Natalie Williams of the Utah Starzz and center Delisha Milton
of the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
"I am honored to represent the United States in preparation for
the 2000 Olympics," said Cooper, a two-time Olympian. "It is a
wonderful experience to compete against the best players from
around the world, as well as to play together with other Americans
on the USA Basketball Senior National Team."
</P>
<P>
The selections were made by the USA Basketball Women's Senior
National Team Committee.
</P>
<P>
"The five players who have been added to the initial core group
are phenomenal," said USA Women's coach Nell Fortner. "If you look
at this team as a whole, it's pretty exciting to think about the
possibilities of what they can accomplish."
</P>
<P>
Nine of the 10 players have competed on at least one gold medal
winning Olympic or World Championship squad. Cooper earned a gold
medal in 1988 and a bronze in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Bolton-Holifield, Leslie, McCray and Staley were all members of
the 1995-96 USA Basketball and 1996 USA Olympic teams that stormed
the country, combined for a 60-0 record and captured the Olympic
gold in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
In World Championship play, Holdsclaw, Milton and Williams
joined the five core group members on the 1998 World Championship
gold medal winning squad. The eight combined to score 700 of the
team's 757 points, or 92.5 percent of the team's offense, at the
1998 World Championships in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Modifying USA Basketball's successful 1995-96 team concept, the
1995-96 team concept, the 1999-2000 USA National Team will train
together and compete in a series of domestic exhibition games
against top NCAA Division I women's teams, as well as several
international tours and tournaments from September 1999 through
March 2000.
</P>
<P>
Breaking for the 2000 WNBA season, the squad will reconvene in
mid-August for its final month of training prior to the September
16-October 1 Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
