<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Rejects U.S. Intervention in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
rejected Saturday a possible U.S. military intervention in
Colombia, warning that it would start "a little Vietnam" in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"This (the U.S. intervention) is no good for us or for
Venezuela or Colombia, nor for our peoples, nor for integration,"
said the president.
</P>
<P>
Chavez told the press during a softball match between armed
forces teams that he will seek a meeting with his Colombian
counterpart Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
He said he insists on mediating a peace between the Colombian
government and the guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan president said he expressed last Tuesday to
United States Political Affairs Undersecretary, Thomas Pickering,
his refusal to see the Colombian problem with "military lens,"
because it would create "a little Vietnam" near Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The United States government has denied that it will send
military forces to combat the guerrillas and drug traffickers in
Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
