<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Keane to Decide his Future at End of Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Irish midfielder Roy Keane has
told Manchester United he is prepared to wait until next summer
before deciding whether to sign a new contract.
</P>
<P>
His announcement means he could leave United in the close
season, with the club receiving no transfer fee.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after United beat Leeds 2-0 in the
Premiership in a noon kick-off on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"At the present time I am undecided as to my future after June
of next year," said Keane in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Over the next few months I will give proper and due
consideration to the club's most recent proposal and I shall make
a decision concerning my future at the end of this season."
</P>
<P>
Keane could then leave the club for free under the Bosman
ruling, which outlawed tranfer fees for out-of-contract players
from the European Union moving within the area.
</P>
<P>
From January 1 next year he will be free to negotiate a
contract with other clubs.
</P>
<P>
The ruling has already been used by a number of players,
including former Liverpool midfielder Steve McManaman who left for
Real Madrid in similar fashion this summer.
</P>
<P>
United themselves benefitted by snapping up goalkeeeper Mark
Bosnich for free from Aston Villa this summer.
</P>
<P>
The problem for clubs is that they cannot recoup any fee by
selling a player immediately if he insists on seeing out his
existing contract.
</P>
<P>
"The new season commenced only a few days ago," added Keane.
</P>
<P>
"It is my earnest wish to be allowed to continue as captain,
free from the burden of continuous media and other speculation as
to my future and to help this great club to what I hope will be
further honours this season."
</P>
<P>
The club are disappointed after "continual and substantial
efforts" to get their skipper to sign the new deal.
</P>
<P>
"We are very hopeful that he will remain a United player for
the rest of his career and that everyone associated with the club,
" said a statement.
</P>
<P>
Keane said he was upset by the criticism aimed at the board and
chairman Martin Edwards because of the contract stalemate.
</P>
<P>
"I have a very good relationship with the supporters, my
manager and the board of directors," he insisted.
</P>
<P>
"I find it both distressing and embarrassing that any criticism
whatsoever should be directed at the board and management of the
club as a consequence of the recent negotiation."
</P>
<P>
Keane says he has not asked for a new deal, or extra money.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to media statements, I have not sought a new contract
from the club nor have I made any financial or other demands of
the club," he said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Edwards believed that although the club's initial
offer to the midfielder had been refused, their second offer was "
acceptable to him in monetary terms."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the sticking point in Keane's mind was
whether he wanted a fresh challenge in his career.
</P>
<P>
It was now the club's duty to persuade him that United could
offer him just what he was looking for.
</P>
<P>
Manager Sir Alex Ferguson was confident that Keane could be
persuaded into staying.
</P>
<P>
"This gives me, the club and the fans the opportunity to show
him how much we need him," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990815.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vialli Extends Sympathy to Own-goal Specialist Sinclair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Chelsea manager Gianluca Vialli
extended the arm of sympathy to Leicester defender Frank Sinclair
after he conceded an own goal for the second successive Saturday
to earn the Londoners a last-gasp draw.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair had put the ball into his own net to earn Arsenal an
injury-time win at Highbury on the opening day of the season.
</P>
<P>
And he became the unwanted headline-maker for the second week
running as he headed past Leicester keeper Tim Flowers just 60
seconds after Muzzy Izzet had put the home side ahead from the
penalty spot.
</P>
<P>
It enabled Chelsea to escape with a 2-2 draw although in truth
the quality of their performance meant they deserved a share of
the spoils.
</P>
<P>
Vialli, who sold Sinclair to Leicester 12 months ago, said: "I
was naturally not too displeased when Frank decided to score an
own goal!
</P>
<P>
"But I do have sympathy for that happening to him, especially
two weeks running. But I'm sure he won't despair and will be
strong enough to cope with that."
</P>
<P>
Vialli admitted: "When Leicester scored the penalty I did not
hold out too much hope but in football anything is possible and we
showed tremendous spirit to earn a point.
</P>
<P>
"We did not start the game well but after the first 20 minutes,
we were in total control until the last 15 minutes and had the
chances. Leicester took advantage of a couple of mistakes."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
